-- Adidas, Bayer, Daimler, Hochtief May Move: German Equity Preview
-- B y   A a r o n   K i r c h f e l d
-- 2011-02-07T07:56:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-06/adidas-bayer-celesio-daimler-hochtief-may-move-german-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Frankfurt. Stock
symbols are in parentheses after company names. Share prices are
from the last close.  The benchmark DAX Index gained 0.3 percent to 7,216.21.    Adidas AG  (ADS GY): Chief Executive Officer Herbert Hainer
said the sporting-goods maker will grow significantly this year
after a strong 2010,  DAF Deutsches Anleger Fernsehen  reported,
citing an interview. The shares fell 0.4 percent to 46.01 euros.    Bayer AG  (BAYN GY): The drugmaker plans to cut 700 jobs in
its health-care unit in Germany, WirtschaftsWoche reported on
its  website , without saying where it got the information. The
stock gained 1.3 percent to 54.85 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI GY): Chief Financial Officer Bodo Uebber
said 2011 will be “a very good year” after “encouraging”
January vehicle sales, DAF Deutsches Anleger Fernsehen reported,
citing a television  interview . The stock fell 0.6 percent to
52.69 euros.    Deutsche Boerse AG  (DB1 GY): Shares of the stock exchange
operator may move after Joachim Nagel, the Bundesbank board
member in charge of markets and information technology, said
high-frequency trading should be subject to minimum holding
periods and volume limits,  WirtschaftsWoche  reported, citing an
interview. The shares rose 0.8 percent to 56.86 euros.       Drillisch AG (DRI GY): The company said it plans to
increase its dividend for 2010 by 70 percent to 50 euro cents
after reporting a 13 percent gain in full-year adjusted earnings
before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization. The
shares rose 2.7 percent to 6.54 euros.    GEA Group AG  (G1A GY): The German engineering firm whose
machines milk a third of the world’s dairy cows said it plans to
increase its dividend to 40 euro cents a share. The shares added
1.1 percent to 21.45 euros.    Hochtief AG  (HOT GY): The construction company doesn’t plan
another capital increase and wants to sell its concessions unit
in an initial public offering or to an investor this year,
 Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung  reported, citing an
interview with Chief Executive Officer Herbert Luetkestratkoetter. The stock increased 2.5 percent to 64.53
euros.    Hornbach Holding AG  (HBH3 GY): The building and gardening
products retailer should reach its forecast for the fiscal year
ending on Feb. 28, Chief Financial Officer Roland Pelka said in
an interview with  Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung . The
shares rose 0.6 percent to 98.61 euros.    Metro AG  (MEO GY): The retailer remains interested in
merging Kaufhof, its department store chain, with rival
Karstadt,  Welt am Sonntag  reported, citing an interview with
Kaufhof stores chief Lovro Mandac. The stock gained 0.6 percent
to 53.40 euros.        SGL Carbon SE  (SGL GR): The company was cut to “neutral”
from “buy” at UBS AG. The shares declined 1 percent to 27.40
euros.        SolarWorld AG  (SWV GY): The company said full-year earnings
before interest and taxes increased to 193 million euros ($262.4
million) from 153 million euros. Separately, the stock was
raised to “outperform” from “neutral” at Credit Suisse Group
AG. The shares jumped 2.3 percent to 7.82 euros.    Volkswagen AG  (VOW3 GY): The carmaker plans to boost the
number of workers for its namesake brand to 290,000 by 2018 from
250,000, with most of the increase in China,  Automobilwoche 
reported, citing internal company documents. The shares lost 0.6
percent to 115.35 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
